  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and conventions against money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC) - Provides a framework for international cooperation against money laundering.\n\n3. The Palermo Convention - Requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish legal mechanisms to combat it.\n\n4. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision - Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering.\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar regulations in the European Union.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
